               <physDesc>
                  <objectDesc form="codex">
                     <supportDesc>
                        <support>parchment</support>
                        <extent>ff. 190</extent>
                     </supportDesc>
                  </objectDesc>
                  <handDesc>
                     <summary>Ashkenazic square script</summary>
                     <handNote>The colophon at the end of no. 1, which is written in a micrographic disposition on <locus>fol. 155r</locus>, indicates only the scribe's name, <persName>Judah</persName>, which is frequently pointed out in the copied text (e.g. <locus>fols. 29r, 103v, 162v</locus>).</handNote>
                  </handDesc>

               </physDesc>
               <history>
                  <origin>
                     <origDate>late 13th century?</origDate>
                     <note>The codicological features (the tpye of parchment as well as the technique of pricking and ruling) match late 13th-cent. dating, which is contradicted by the 1384 date of the second letter of divorce on <locus>fol. 68r</locus> (in addition to the first letter of divorce on <locus>fol. 67v</locus>, dated 1284). But since both letters share the same place of writing and the same date, apart from the extra century in the second one, this might well have been added by mistake.</note>
                     <origPlace>France?</origPlace>
                  </origin>
                  <provenance>
                  </provenance>
                  <acquisition>It belonged to David Oppenheimer's (1667-1735) library, which was purchased by the Bodleian Library in 1829.</acquisition>
               </history>
